/www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/meet-al-nienhuis-hernando-countys-new-top-cop/1142997 |title=Meet Al Nienhuis, Hernando's new top cop \u2013 Tampa Bay Times |publisher=Tampabay.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n|party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1951|5|26}}\n|birth_place = [[Evergreen Park, Illinois]]\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|spouse = Wendy Nugent\n|children=3\n|residence =[[Spring Hill, Florida]]\n|alma_mater =[[Saint Leo University]] <small>(B.A.)</small><br>[[Troy University]] <small>(M.P.A.)</small>\n|occupation =\n|profession =Sheriff\n|religion = [[United Methodist Church|Methodist]]\n|website = {{URL|http://nugent.house.gov}}\n<!--Military service-->\n|nickname =\n|allegiance =\n|branch = [[Illinois Air National Guard]]\n|serviceyears = 1969\u20131975\n|rank =\n|unit =\n|commands =\n|battles =\n|awards =\n}}\n\n'''Richard B.''' \"'''Rich'''\" '''Nugent''' (born May 26, 1951) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|FL|11}}. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He used to be the [[Hernando County Sheriff's Office|Sheriff]] of [[Hernando County, Florida]]. On November 2, 2010 Richard Nugent defeated Democratic nominee James Piccillo, to replace retiring Congresswoman [[Ginny Brown-Waite]]. Nugent is a member of the [[Tea Party Caucus]]. On November 2, 2015, Nugent announced that he will leave Congress at the end of his term (January 3, 2017).<ref name=\"Villages-News.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.villages-news.com/congressman-rich-nugent-announces-intent-to-step-down-from-congress/ |title=Congressman Rich Nugent announces intent to step down from Congress |publisher=Villages-News.com |date=2015-11-02 |accessdate=2015-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early law enforcement career==\nNugent was born on May 26, 1951. He is a native of [[Evergreen Park, Illinois]],<ref name=\"townhall1\">{{cite web|url=http://election.townhall.com/election-2010/state/FL/candidate/richard-b-nugent |title=2012 Election: Presidential, National & Local Candidates, News, Results, Polls |publisher=Election.townhall.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> a suburb of Chicago.<ref>[http://nugent.house.gov/about-me/full-biography ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110116052809/http://nugent.house.gov/about-me/full-biography |date=January 16, 2011 }}</ref> His father was a [[steel worker]] and his mother was a homemaker.<ref name=\"whorunsgov1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.whorunsgov.com/Profiles/Richard_Nugent |title=Richard Nugent (R-Fla.) \u2013 The Washington Post |publisher=Whorunsgov.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\nAfter high school Nugent joined the [[Illinois Air National Guard]] for six years. He then continued serving as a police officer in the city of [[Romeoville, Illinois]].<ref name=\"house2\">{{cite web|url=http://nugent.house.gov/ |title=Congressman Richard Nugent |publisher=Nugent.house.gov |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> After serving as a police officer in Romeoville for 12 years, Nugent and his family moved to [[Hernando County]], Florida in 1984, where he joined the Hernando County Sheriff's office as a deputy.<ref name=\"house2\"/>\n\nNugent graduated from [[St. Leo College]], located in St. Leo, Pasco County, Florida with a Bachelor of Arts Degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saintleo.edu/About-SLU/History |title=History &#124; Saint Leo University |publisher=Saintleo.edu |date=1999-08-24 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>  He went on to earn a Master of Arts Degree from [[Troy State]] University.<ref name=\"whorunsgov1\"/>  In 1991 Congressman Nugent graduated from the FBI National Academy.<ref name=\"townhall1\"/>\n\n==Sheriff of Hernando County==\nNugent was elected Sheriff of Hernando County in 2000, defeating James E. \"Eddie\" McConnell.<ref name=\"sptimes2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2004/10/26/news_pf/Hernando/Keep_Nugent_as_sheriff.shtml |title=Hernando: Keep Nugent as sheriff |publisher=Sptimes.com |date=2004-10-26 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\n===Election results===\nHe was elected Sheriff in 2000 and was re-elected in 2004 and 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nugentforcongress.com/index.cfm/meet-rich |title=Meet Rich \u2013 Home \u2013 Rich Nugent for Congress |publisher=Nugentforcongress.com |date=2010-05-22 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\nIn 2000, Nugent was endorsed by incumbent Sheriff Tom Mylander. In 2004, he was endorsed by the [[St. Petersburg Times]]\n\n[[Image:Sheriff Richard Nugent-RBN WhiteShirt 150.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Sheriff Nugent]]\n{{Election box begin | title=2000 Hernando County Sheriff election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stpetersburgtimes.com/News/110900/Election2000/Election_results_.shtml |title=Tampa Bay, Florida news &#124; Tampa Bay Times/St. Pete Times |publisher=Stpetersburgtimes.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/Archive/110800/Hernando.shtml |title=St. Petersburg Times Online: Hernando County news |publisher=Sptimes.com |date=2000-11-08 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Rich Nugent'''\n  |votes      = 31,204\n  |percentage = 49.0\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Eddie McConnell\n  |votes      = 29,334\n  |percentage = 46.1\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n  |party      = Independent\n  |candidate  = Michael Robinson\n  |votes      = 3,088\n  |percentage = 4.9\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin | title=2004 Hernando County Sheriff election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=142577 |title=Hernando County, FL Sheriff Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2004 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Rich Nugent''' (Incumbent)\n  |votes      = 48,771\n  |percentage = 61.6\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Eddie McConnell\n  |votes      = 30,372\n  |percentage = 38.4\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin | title=2008 Hernando County Sheriff election<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridastatefop.org/pdf_files/2008sheriffGENERALELECTIONRESULTS.pdf |title=2008 GENERAL ELECTION REPORT |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Rich Nugent''' (Incumbent)\n  |votes      = 62,807\n  |percentage = 73.6\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Luke Frazier\n  |votes      = 22,153\n  |percentage = 26.0\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n  |party      = Independent\n  |candidate  = Michael Robinson\n  |votes      = 334\n  |percentage = 0.4\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2010 election===\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2010#District 5}}\n\nRepublican Congresswoman [[Ginny Brown-Waite]] decided not to run for re-election in the 5th Congressional District of Florida, due to health concerns. She asked Nugent to run for her seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/politics/elections/nugent-jumps-ahead-in-gop-race-in-5th-congressional-district/1117237 |title=Nugent jumps ahead in GOP race in 5th Congressional District \u2013 Tampa Bay Times |publisher=Tampabay.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> Nugent won the Republican primary and was endorsed during his campaign by former Governor of Arkansas [[Mike Huckabee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nugentforcongress.com/index.cfm/endorsements?p=featured-endorsements |title=Featured Endorsements \u2013 Endorsements \u2013 Rich Nugent for Congress |publisher=Nugentforcongress.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://my.huckpac.com/?Fuseaction=Candidates.View&State_id=62 |title=Huck PAC \u2013 Candidates |publisher=My.huckpac.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> and by several Florida newspapers, including the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]], [[Tampa Bay Times]]'', and the ''[[Tampa Tribune]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nugentforcongress.com/index.cfm/newpaper-endorsements-of-rich |title=Newspaper Endorsements \u2013 Endorsements \u2013 Rich Nugent for Congress |publisher=Nugentforcongress.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\nNugent beat [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] favorite Jason Sager in the primary and won against Democrat Jim Piccillo in the general election.  ''The New York Times'' had rated this race as solidly Republican.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown |first=Theresa |url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/house/florida/5 |title=Florida 5th District Race Profile \u2013 Election 2010 \u2013 The New York Times |publisher=Elections.nytimes.com |date=2010-12-10 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>  The Ocala online newspaper reported that In the 5th Congressional District, Nugent swept past Democrat Jim Piccillo, a political newcomer from Lutz, receiving 67 percent of the vote to 33 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson |first=Bill |url=http://www.ocala.com/article/20101102/ARTICLES/101109916?p=3&tc=pg |title=Marion County congressional roundup 2010 |publisher=Ocala.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\nIn his first two months in Congress he co-sponsored 29 pieces of legislation, including H.R. 2 \u2013 Repeal of the Health Care Law Act, H.R.25 \u2013 The Fair Tax Act of 2011, H.R. 49 \u2013 American Energy Independence and Price Reduction Act, H.R. 121 \u2013 Congressional Budget Accountability Act, H.R. 127 \u2013 to deauthorize appropriation of funds to carry out the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act and the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010, H.R. 144 \u2013 Small Business Paperwork Mandate Elimination Act of 2011,  H.R. 154 \u2013 Defund the Individual Mandate Act, Hr. 177 \u2013 Death Tax Repeal Act, H.R. 178 \u2013 Military Surviving Spouses Equity Act, H.R. 333 \u2013 Disabled Veterans Tax Termination Act and H.R. 42` \u2013 To eliminate automatic pay adjustments for Members of Congress.\nNugent has also co-sponsored H.J. Res.1 \u2013 Proposing a [[balanced budget amendment]] to the Constitution of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/R?d112:FLD004:@1%28Rep.+Nugent+Richard%29: |title=Bill Summary & Status |publisher=Thomas.loc.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\n;Spending cuts\nNugent is against what he terms out of control spending presently happening in Washington.  He opposed the $700 billion bailout by President George W. Bush, a temporary fix for de-regulation of the banking and finance industries, two unfunded Bush-era wars, and a decades-long wage decrease.  He also opposed the Obama Administration's $862 billion stimulus package.\n\n;Tax Reform\nNugent signed on as a co-sponsor of H.R. 25, better known as \"[[FairTax|The Fair Tax]]\".  This legislation introduced by Rep. Rob Woodall (R-GA) would abolish the Internal Revenue Service (IRS), repeal the federal income tax, and replace it with a transparent tax on consumption.<ref>[http://nugent.house.gov/issue/taxes ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110602055335/http://nugent.house.gov/issue/taxes |date=June 2, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Nugent signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Nugent_Richard.pdf</ref>\n\n;Health Care Act\nNugent opposed the passage of President Barack Obama's health care legislation and has vowed to work for its repeal. He has stated that he is open to listening to anybody's plan to save and reform Medicare so long as benefits are completely unchanged for those 55 and up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nugentforcongress.com/index.cfm/issues |title=Issues \u2013 Rich Nugent for Congress |publisher=Nugentforcongress.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nNugent serves on the Committee on House Administration.<ref name=\"house1\">{{cite web|url=http://cha.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8&Itemid=5 |title=Committee on House Administration |publisher=Cha.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> Nugent formerly served on the House Committee on Rules .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rules.house.gov/singlepages.aspx?NewsID=3&RSBD=4 |title=House Committee on Rules \u2013 Members of the Committee on Rules |publisher=Rules.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> In January 2015, Nugent was removed from that committee, in an apparent retribution for voting against John Boehner as House Speaker.<ref>http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/238753-house-panel-replaces-members-after-boehner-rebellion</ref>\n\nNugent belongs to several House caucus groups, including the Congressional Sportsman's Caucus,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsmenslink.org/media_room/eblast/press_releases/Congressional_Sportsmen%E2%80%99s_Caucus_Leaders_Set_for_112th_Congress |title=Congressional Sportsmen\u2019s Caucus Leaders Set for 112th Congress &#124; congressional sportsmen's foundation |publisher=Sportsmenslink.org |date=2011-01-05 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> The Constitution Caucus,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanevents.com/article.php?id=14730 |title=New Constitutional Caucus Defends Tenth Amendment |publisher=Human Events |date= |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref> The Military Family Caucus,<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3731/is_201012/ai_n56626223/ ]{{dead link|date=May 2012}}</ref> the Congressional Cement Caucus, and the [[Tea Party Caucus#Members of House Caucus|Tea Party Caucus]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1975, Rich married Wendy Nugent and they have three boys. The Nugent family have been members of the First United Methodist Church of Spring Hill since 1985.\n\nOn November 2, 2015, Nugent announced that he would leave Congress at the end of his term on January 3, 2017.<ref name=\"Villages-News.com\"/> Among the reasons given for leaving office, Nugent cited a desire to spend more time with family: \u201cAfter five years of living out of a suitcase, saying goodbye almost weekly to my beloved wife, and seeing pictures of the grandkids instead of spending more of that quality time with them, the tug of being apart from family has just become too great.\"<ref name=\"Villages-News.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nugent.house.gov/ Congressman Rich Nugent] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.nugentforcongress.com/ Rich Nugent for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Richard_Nugent_%5BR-11%5D|Richard Nugent}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Richard Nugent}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = N000185 | ballot = Rich_Nugent | nndb = 336/000112997 | votesmart = 124333 | govtrack = 412409 | opencong = 412409 | rollcall = 32346 | politifact = | ontheissues = FL/Rich_Nugent.htm | congress = richard-nugent/N000185 | fec = H0FL05139 | opensecrets = N00032441 | assets = richard-nugent | legistorm = 2738/Rep_Richard_Nugent_FL.html | followthemoney = | c-span = richardnugent | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAt0HaKP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Florida\n| district=5\n| before=[[Ginny Brown-Waite]]\n| after=[[Corrine Brown]]|years=January 3, 2011 \u2013 January 3, 2013}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Florida\n| district=11\n| before=[[Kathy Castor]]\n| a